[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there a clean way to get the size of a structure field in const context? I only found this <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/61046063/how-to-get-the-size-of-a-struct-field-in-rust-without-instantiating-it\">stackoverflow thread</a>.</p>\n<p>The reason I need this is because the kernel gives my module a pointer to this field in order to store some private data for later use. I want to fail compilation if the type I intend to store in that memory is too large. On the C side there is a #define, but involves the <code>sizeof_field</code> and is thus not converted by bindgen.</p>",
        "id": 419130916,
        "sender_full_name": "Valentin Obst",
        "timestamp": 1706738507
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is adding a helper function in rust/helpers.c exporting from C what you need (the macro/sizeof) an option?</p>",
        "id": 419208934,
        "sender_full_name": "Dirk Behme",
        "timestamp": 1706780882
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If I understand correctly, this would require that my abstractions perform a runtime check to verify that the struct defined by the module fits into the storage that the kernel provides. Ideally I'd like the compilation of such a module to fail.</p>",
        "id": 419224708,
        "sender_full_name": "Valentin Obst",
        "timestamp": 1706786370
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe anything like this (see <a href=\"https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2021&amp;gist=c3e261786c770ee7cd1c949b9b9230a9\">Playground</a>) ?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">struct</span> <span class=\"nc\">TheStruct</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">foo</span>: <span class=\"p\">[</span>::<span class=\"n\">std</span>::<span class=\"n\">os</span>::<span class=\"n\">raw</span>::<span class=\"n\">c_char</span><span class=\"p\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">100</span><span class=\"k\">usize</span><span class=\"p\">],</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">// other fields...</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span> <span class=\"nf\">main</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"fm\">dbg!</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">get_size_of_return_type</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">|</span><span class=\"n\">s</span>: <span class=\"nc\">TheStruct</span><span class=\"o\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">foo</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">fn</span> <span class=\"nf\">get_size_of_return_type</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">F</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">_f</span>: <span class=\"nc\">F</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>-&gt; <span class=\"kt\">usize</span>\n<span class=\"nc\">where</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">F</span>: <span class=\"nb\">FnOnce</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span>-&gt; <span class=\"nc\">U</span>\n<span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">size</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">std</span>::<span class=\"n\">mem</span>::<span class=\"n\">size_of</span>::<span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">();</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">// For kernel code replace std by core</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">if</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">size</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">90</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"fm\">compile_error!</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s\">\"Size too large\"</span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">size</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Inspired by the given <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/61046063/how-to-get-the-size-of-a-struct-field-in-rust-without-instantiating-it\">stackoverflow thread</a>.</p>",
        "id": 419236946,
        "sender_full_name": "Dirk Behme",
        "timestamp": 1706790950
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Unfortunately this does not work in const context (<a href=\"https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2021&amp;gist=c2e2c57badd4a7098040db436a5f2fcf\">Playground</a>). The macro works and looks sound, however, I thought there might be a better way since this was posted three years ago.</p>",
        "id": 419244010,
        "sender_full_name": "Valentin Obst",
        "timestamp": 1706793507
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Turning <code>get_size_of_return_type</code> into const and using an static assertion would be the way to go. In <code>kernel</code> we have the <code>build_assert</code> macro which performs the assertion in a const context or expands into a panic otherwise.</p>",
        "id": 419285815,
        "sender_full_name": "Martin Rodriguez Reboredo",
        "timestamp": 1706805313
    }
]